		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2012"></a><br><code>sle2012/paper12</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012</a> paper:</span><br><i>Island Grammar-Based Parsing Using GLL and Tom</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AliAfroozeh.html">Ali Afroozeh</a>, <a href="../profile/JeanChristopheBach.html">Jean-Christophe Bach</a>, <a href="../profile/MarkvandenBrand.html">Mark van den Brand</a>, <a href="../profile/AdrianJohnstone.html">Adrian Johnstone</a>, <a href="../profile/MaartenManders.html">Maarten Manders</a>, <a href="../profile/PierreEtienneMoreau.html">Pierre-Etienne Moreau</a>, <a href="../profile/ElizabethScott.html">Elizabeth Scott</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_13">10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_13</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The core contribution is a parsing technique and its tool-level realization using generalized parsing (GLL) and Tom.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> Island grammars are motivated by composing parsers with “holes” for embedded/unknown fragments, supporting language integration.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The approach relies on grammar formalisms and rewriting infrastructure (Tom) to specify and implement the parsing strategy.
</li></ul></li></ul>
